Harry Potter Episode 8 - Weasleysâ€™ cars - K-means cluster analysis

library(tidyverse)  # data wrangling
library(cluster)    # clustering 
library(factoextra) # clustering and visualization
library(gridExtra) # arranging plots

Data pre-processing

Load data

data <- read.delim("weasley_cars.txt")

head(data)
rownames(data) <- data$car_brands
data <- data[,-c(1)]

Scale data

Standardise or scale the data by transforming the variables so that they have a mean of zero and standard deviation of one.
We scale the data in order to make the variables comparable.

# preserve original dataset
ori <- data

data <- scale(data)
data <- data.frame(data)

head(data)

Computing the distance or dissimilarity between observation pairs

We can use the factoextra package to compute and visualise the distance matrix.
The get_dist function is used to compute a distance matrix between the rows of a data matrix. The default distance is Euclidean.
The fviz_dist function is used to visualise the distance matrix.

distance <- get_dist(data)
fviz_dist(distance, gradient = list(low = "#00AFBB", mid = "white", high = "#FC4E07"))

In the heatmap, red represents dissimilarities and turquoise represents similarities.

Perform K-Means clustering

We start by specifying the number of clusters (k). We will group the data into two clusters by specifying centers = 2.
Specifying nstart = 25 means that the algorithm will generate 25 initial configurations.

k2 <- kmeans(data, centers = 2, nstart = 25)
str(k2)

Visualising results

fviz_cluster(k2, data = data)

Letâ€™s try different Ks

We can specify k as 3, 4 and 5 and examine the results.

k3 <- kmeans(data, centers = 3, nstart = 25)
k4 <- kmeans(data, centers = 4, nstart = 25)
k5 <- kmeans(data, centers = 5, nstart = 25)

# plots to compare
p1 <- fviz_cluster(k2, geom = "point", data = data) + ggtitle("k = 2")
p2 <- fviz_cluster(k3, geom = "point",  data = data) + ggtitle("k = 3")
p3 <- fviz_cluster(k4, geom = "point",  data = data) + ggtitle("k = 4")
p4 <- fviz_cluster(k5, geom = "point",  data = data) + ggtitle("k = 5")

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, p4, nrow = 2)

Based on the graphs, we can see whether the clusters are well separated. However, the graphs donâ€™t tell us what the optimal number of clusters is.

Methods for getting the optimal number of clusters

Method 1 - Elbow

The main aim of clustering is that we want to minimise within-cluster variation. Thus, for each k, we can calculate the total within-cluster sum of square (wss) and plot the values according to the number of clusters.

set.seed(123)

# computing the within-cluster sum of square
fviz_nbclust(data, kmeans, method = "wss")

Based on the graph above, the â€˜elbowâ€™ (region where the line starts to bend) occurs at 4, which suggests that the optimal number of clusters is 4.

Method 2 - Average Silhouette

The average silhouette method measures the quality of a clustering by determining how well each object lies within a cluster. The higher the average silhouette value, the better the clustering.

This method computes the average silhouette of observations for different k values. We can simply specify method = silhouette.

fviz_nbclust(data, kmeans, method = "silhouette")

The graph above demonstrates that the maximum average silhouette was reached with 2 clusters. 3 clusters came in second place.

Method 3 - Gap Statistic

This method measures how different the total intra-cluster variation is, for different k values, between observed data and reference data with a random uniform distribution (a distribution with no clustering).

# calculate gap statistic
set.seed(123)
gap_stat <- clusGap(data, FUN = kmeans, nstart = 25,
                    K.max = 10, B = 50)

print(gap_stat, method = "firstmax")
## Clustering Gap statistic ["clusGap"] from call:

fviz_gap_stat(gap_stat)

Based on the above graph, the optimal number of clusters is 3 clusters.

What is the optimal number of clusters?
- Elbow method = 4 clusters
- Average silhouette method = 2 clusters (next best = 3)
- Gap statistic method = 3 clusters

Final clustering with k = 3

# generate k-means clustering with k = 3
set.seed(123)
final <- kmeans(data, 3, nstart = 25)

fviz_cluster(final, data = data)

Getting descriptive statistics for the clusters

ori %>%
  mutate(Cluster = final$cluster) %>%
  group_by(Cluster) %>%
  summarise_all("mean")

The table shows the average values for the four variables within each cluster.
